00:05:01,283 --> 00:05:28,894
and where the arrow is bent you put it onto a surface so the bow is sticking upwards and then you rub it up and down with a piece of wood and the friction of it creates heat it's easily bendable and then when it cools it'll stay straight there were other ways but this is the way that i think the buddha was referring to because of course training the mind you've got to keep bringing it back bringing it back

33
00:05:32,620 --> 00:06:00,483
the second one about the fish a slightly interesting word there for fish is uh warija now wari is water and ja means born so born in the water hence a fish now as a fish quivers when he's taken out of a watery home so the mind quivers when taken away from the realm of mara so now

34
00:06:00,716 --> 00:06:07,187
we are of course entranced by our senses, what we see, what we hear, what we taste and so on.

35
00:06:07,968 --> 00:06:17,023
And suddenly to find ourselves in this inner quiet place, not feeding the senses, then obviously those old habits go berserk.

36
00:06:17,043 --> 00:06:22,372
They want to be back out into the world, engaging with Mara, the enticer.

37
00:06:24,475 --> 00:06:27,720
And so just like a fish taken out of water,

38
00:06:28,072 --> 00:06:37,906
you know, almost gasping for oxygen and quivering, so the mind is gasping for these sensual delights.

39
00:06:40,410 --> 00:06:42,874
So that's a good, I think that's a very good image.

40
00:06:42,894 --> 00:06:48,141
The Buddha is very good at, you know, these little metaphors just to get across his meaning.

41
00:06:48,742 --> 00:06:50,564
He says some people think like that.

42
00:06:50,685 --> 00:06:56,374
So people have, you know, imaginative poetic minds and others have very intellectual

43
00:06:56,540 --> 00:06:58,923
Most of us, of course, are in between.

44
00:06:58,983 --> 00:07:07,634
So now, having said all that, does he somewhere give ideas on how to train the mind?

45
00:07:09,697 --> 00:07:15,665
Well, now for this, we have to go to the scriptures themselves.

46
00:07:16,786 --> 00:07:19,088
Just before I go, I'll just read the commentary.

47
00:07:19,629 --> 00:07:25,617
So there's a commentary on all these Dhammapada verses and on the scriptures.

48
00:07:26,442 --> 00:07:31,185
The story of this verse is the same as the previous one, so they're both much the same.

49
00:07:32,247 --> 00:07:41,456
Our mind is indeed wavering, writhing and difficult to restrain, and now they want to give us an image like a snake or a young branch.

50
00:07:42,637 --> 00:07:47,661
So an arrow maker making an arrow has to straighten it, otherwise it would be worthless.

51
00:07:48,041 --> 00:07:52,146
In the same way, we have to straighten the mind, otherwise it won't hit the goal.

52
00:07:52,466 --> 00:07:54,728
The goal, of course, is nirvana.

53
00:07:57,812 --> 00:08:00,576
Okay, so now how to stop thinking.

54
00:08:00,656 --> 00:08:04,843
So this is in the middle discourses, the Majjhima Nikaya number 20.

55
00:08:05,925 --> 00:08:07,327
You can look it up yourself there.

56
00:08:08,088 --> 00:08:14,298
I shall only mention the various ways in which it can be done and then we'll see.

57
00:08:14,778 --> 00:08:22,891
So the first thing is that the mendicant should focus on some of the foundation of meditation connected with what is skillful.

58
00:08:23,581 --> 00:08:51,445
so uh for instance if uh erotic if erotic images appear in the mind one thinks of the foulness of the body and that definitely undoes the eroticism so that's one example a food when you're eating food you're feeling greedy you know you're overeating then just imagine what happens to the food until its final elimination and that would definitely put you off eating much more

59
00:08:52,807 --> 00:08:58,196
So it says here that we send your desire, always try to create the other, the opposite.

60
00:08:58,556 --> 00:09:05,386
Now you're not trying to develop disgust and self-hatred and all that, or hatred towards the body rather.

61
00:09:06,168 --> 00:09:07,308
You're just trying to balance it.

62
00:09:07,389 --> 00:09:15,902
So when something pleasant comes up, which is an obsessive thing, one brings up the opposite and it cancels each other out.

63
00:09:16,062 --> 00:09:20,688
So it's just a way of undermining these unwholesome habits.

64
00:09:23,234 --> 00:09:49,360
if it's directed towards an inanimate object then of course uh it's impermanence so you might be wandering around the shops you know uh escaping from lockdown and seeing all these wonderful clothes and uh and then you recognize that well you know the body's impermanent clothes are impermanent everything's impermanent so i don't demise that greed that's what we're concerned with not concerned with not buying clothes we need to dress ourselves yeah

65
00:09:51,482 --> 00:10:18,822
when thoughts of hate arise of course towards the other the opposite is loving kindness and if it's towards uh an inanimate object and there was a greedy desire to to to have something and uh see it in its in its characteristics uh the four great elements you know that it's it is actually just something that comes together with pressure with heat with um

66
00:10:19,106 --> 00:10:43,038
something that is elastic elastic and uh and moving a movement in other words just deconstruct it just see it for what it actually is and uh thoughts with delusion are slightly different uh that would be something like doubt or something like that so then of course it says just uh live with the you know

67
00:10:43,356 --> 00:10:52,268
Put yourself under the guidance of a teacher, study the Dharma, inquiring into its meaning, listen to the Dharma and inquire into its causes.

68
00:10:52,708 --> 00:11:06,866
So here we have number one is the mendicant should focus on some other foundation of meditation, on some other object, usually the opposite or something that undermines whatever is causing the mind to wander.

69
00:11:10,001 --> 00:11:18,072
The second one is to, you know, this is if it keeps going, if that doesn't work, and to examine the drawbacks of these thoughts.

70
00:11:18,793 --> 00:11:26,423
So just remembering that unworthiness of evil thoughts, it causes us to be shameful.

71
00:11:26,523 --> 00:11:35,254
Now, shame doesn't have very good support in modern psychotherapy, but that would be neurotic shame.

72
00:11:35,315 --> 00:11:39,519
That is a shame to do with self-worth, with self-esteem, you know, that

73
00:11:39,870 --> 00:12:07,009
if that were if if i did that it wouldn't be me that sort of statement that we have about ourselves and some sometimes we feel less of an inner shame you know thinking about these things or getting ourselves into into those sorts of mental places so this is only about thoughts remember and of course to understand that there are dangers because when you develop unwholesome states

74
00:12:07,158 --> 00:12:35,899
they do you know grow within ourselves and every so often they'll escape through what we say and even through what we do so there has to be a little bit of dread of consequences there the next one is a is a little bit difficult for us to try to ignore them and forget about them so when the mind is just restless now sometimes the mind is is just restless it's just moving all over the place in which case

75
00:12:36,166 --> 00:12:41,390
The best thing to do is just, as it were, push it aside and bring the attention back into the body.

76
00:12:42,131 --> 00:12:45,455
So sometimes that works, sometimes they do forget them.

77
00:12:45,836 --> 00:12:50,681
Of course, here we're talking about training the attention to be still.

78
00:12:51,321 --> 00:13:01,751
This is obviously a little bit of suppression here, but we can deal with these things much better when we've attained some level of steadiness of the mind.

79
00:13:05,393 --> 00:13:09,438
And then it says you should stop stopping the formation of thoughts.

80
00:13:09,818 --> 00:13:14,745
Now that's interesting because the Pali uses the word Sankara.

81
00:13:14,765 --> 00:13:22,996
Now Sankara are our habits, our volitional formations, is what we have created in ourselves through acts of will.

82
00:13:23,457 --> 00:13:33,291
All our negative speaking, all our anger, all our anxiety, all that is self-created just as much as our love, our happiness and joy.

83
00:13:34,705 --> 00:13:42,032
So here it actually translates as a condition to stopping the causing of thought.

84
00:13:42,812 --> 00:13:45,916
Now here we can ask the question, what is the cause?

85
00:13:47,498 --> 00:13:49,220
Why is this happening in me?

86
00:13:49,539 --> 00:14:00,291
Now that's getting us close to a more vipassana position where we would then go into the body to examine the actual mental state that's causing the thoughts to arise.

87
00:14:00,996 --> 00:14:02,538
And of course, that's where we would stay.

88
00:14:02,619 --> 00:14:07,964
We would stay there investigating, feeling, allowing this mental state to express itself.

89
00:14:13,889 --> 00:14:27,364
And then finally, if all that doesn't work, the Buddha says, with teeth clenched and tongue pressed against the roof of the mouth, they should squeeze, squash and torture the mind with mind.

90
00:14:27,884 --> 00:14:30,767
That sounds pretty heavy, but here,

91
00:14:31,051 --> 00:14:37,457
what the Buddha is saying that we should really replace an unwholesome thought with a wholesome thought.

92
00:14:38,197 --> 00:14:44,485
Now, this is especially useful if you're trying to develop a particular mental state, such as loving kindness.

93
00:14:44,965 --> 00:14:59,320
If you find that you're very involved in some sort of hateful thing, angry place, anxious place, doesn't matter what it is, one really just keeps those beads, you use beads, you know,

94
00:14:59,687 --> 00:15:07,299
May all beings be happy, may all beings be safe, may all beings be healthy, may all beings, and you just pound, pound, pound.

95
00:15:07,581 --> 00:15:16,835
And what you're doing is creating a mental state, right, which will eventually sit on top, keep these unfortunate states underneath.

96
00:15:17,616 --> 00:15:20,081
And you are developing that mental state.

97
00:15:20,100 --> 00:15:26,049
You know, when we practice this, we are developing loving kindness, but we're not, of course, looking at what's underneath this stuff.

98
00:15:27,667 --> 00:15:36,398
But again, the purpose is to still the mind, to stop this energy going up into the head and creating this vortex of energy.

99
00:15:38,559 --> 00:15:49,293
So, you know, just to go through them again, focus on some other opposite to what we're actually experiencing.

100
00:15:49,312 --> 00:15:52,898
If it's something to do with anger or hatred, you do the loving kindness.

101
00:15:53,477 --> 00:15:57,403
Examine the drawbacks, feel the shame, the dread of consequences.

102
00:15:57,754 --> 00:16:01,058
Just ignore them and, you know, just put them away.

103
00:16:01,078 --> 00:16:05,725
And then you can go into the causes of those thoughts.

104
00:16:07,006 --> 00:16:09,289
You know, why are they happening?

105
00:16:09,750 --> 00:16:21,145
And finally, to dampen it down by strong loving kindness practice or compassion practice, joy practice or peacefulness practice.

106
00:16:21,166 --> 00:16:22,407
May all beings be peaceful.

107
00:16:22,447 --> 00:16:23,589
May I be peaceful.

108
00:16:24,028 --> 00:16:25,672
May all beings be peaceful.

109
00:16:26,131 --> 00:16:26,832
Something like that.

110
00:16:27,977 --> 00:16:33,222
So what we've done is we've read these two little verses.

111
00:16:35,405 --> 00:16:37,748
The mind is excitable and unsteady.

112
00:16:37,927 --> 00:16:41,111
It is difficult to control and to restrain.

113
00:16:41,152 --> 00:16:45,996
The wise one trains his mind to be upright as a fletcher straightens an arrow.

114
00:16:46,356 --> 00:16:48,658
That's a slightly different translation.

115
00:16:49,440 --> 00:16:53,985
As a fish quivers when taken out of its watery home and thrown onto dry ground,

116
00:16:54,370 --> 00:17:01,342
So does the mind quiver when it is taken out of the sensual world to escape from the realm of Mara.

117
00:17:03,046 --> 00:17:18,133
So, I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused even greater confusion, and that you will, by your devotion to practice, liberate yourselves from all suffering sooner rather than later.

